article.headline: Sales' 18 points paced Connecticut
article.linkText: Sun pull away down the stretch, break Fever
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Nykesha Sales' second-half spurt got
the Connecticut Sun going in the right direction against the
Indiana Fever and in the WNBA standings.

Sales scored 14 of her 18 points in the second half to lead the
Sun to a 66-55 victory over the Fever on Sunday night. Connecticut
moved past Indiana into third place in the Eastern Conference with
eight games remaining.

"Right now, every game is being defended by both teams like its
a playoff game," Sun coach Mike Thibault said. "What it comes
down to is who makes the fewest mistakes or who can get two or
three stops in a row and convert them at the other end down the
stretch."

The Sun were coming off a 48-45 loss to last-place Washington on
Friday in which they shot a season low 23 percent.

"The biggest key was how we got Nykesha going to start the
second half," Thibault said. "We got her some big shots. We had a
lot of people contribute tonight in different ways and shared
responsibilities. We did a good job of finding the right person."

Sales shot 1-for-5 in the first half but scored eight straight
points after intermission to give the Sun a 35-23 lead.

Indiana battled back several times and took a 52-51 lead on
Kristen Rasmussen's 3-pointer with 4:21 left.

The Sun closed with a 15-3 run in the final 2:41 to put the
Fever away. Katie Douglas scored six of her nine points in that
spurt.

"We knew how important this game was," Sun guard Shannon
Johnson said. "Playing against a team like Washington, its very
frustrating when we lose a game like that when we know how good we
are."

Johnson scored 11 of her 13 points in the first half. She also
had eight assists and six rebounds. Taj McWilliams-Franklin added
eight points, seven rebounds and a career-high five blocks for
Connecticut.

Tamika Catchings had 14 points and 11 rebounds to lead the
Fever. Rasmussen and Natalie Williams each had 11 points and nine
rebounds.

"We gave it a good run," Fever coach Nell Fortner said. "We
went up one, but they came out and took it at us, and we couldn't
get a stop."

Former UConn center Kelly Schumacher had six points for the
Fever.

Indiana was 11-for-11 from the free-throw line. The Fever has
made 33 straight, including a franchise-best 15-for-15 effort
against Detroit on Saturday.
